passages.text: KAR delivered a strong 1H25 result, with both underlying EBITDA and NPAT ahead of expectations. However, key factors contributing to the beat were positive inventory movements and accounting for flotel and FPSO transition and relocation costs below the line. Bauna's strong performance during this period led to an upward revision of the FY25 production guidance and a reduction in full- year cost guidance. However, challenges at SPS- 92 are anticipated to impact production over the next 12 to 18 months. Importantly, reserves at Bauna were revised higher following the completion of the FPSO acquisition, extending Bauna's expected operational life from 2023 to 2039. With a clearer outlook at Bauna, the focus shifts towards the transition to operatorship over the next year and advancing growth projects Neon and Who Dat East. While we do see operational risks with KAR taking the reins of the FPSO, we believe KAR is well- positioned to continue improving availability at Bauna, now managing the maintenance schedule, with upside to future production from organic growth. With the stock trading below our NPV of \(\) 2.30\((previously\) \ \(2.10\) ), we maintain our Overweight rating.

Underlying EBITDA ahead of expectations: Underlying EBITDA of US \(\) 192m\(was 21\%\) above prior estimates, driven by positive inventory movements of US\) \ \(17.2m\) and flotel and FPSO costs taken below the line. The interim dividend of 2.4 Acps exceeded expectations of 1.0 Acps, and net debt of US\) \ \(225m\) was better than anticipated. FY25 production guidance was revised upwards by \(4\%\) at the midpoint, despite issues with the electrical submersible pump at SPS- 92, resulting in a \(10\%\) reduction in FY25 unit production cost guidance.

Reserves upgrade at Bauna: With the Bauna FPSO acquisition complete, KAR assessed the new cost structure and life extension plans, increasing 2P reserves by \(35\%\) compared to December 2024. This analysis extends Bauna's economic life from 2032 to 2039, when the Production Concession expires. KAR plans to invest US \(55 - 65m\) in an FPSO revitalization campaign in 2026 and approximately US \(80 - 90m\) for life extension activities between 2030 and 2034, including two flotel campaigns and equipment upgrades. Abandonment costs have increased from US \(174.9m\) in 2032 to US \(260.0m\) in 2039 due to FPSO inclusion and changes in scope, activity durations and vessel rates.

Growth projects progressing: KAR is focused on improving operational reliability at Bauna and pursuing organic growth opportunities, Neon and Who Dat East. Discussions with external parties on farming down a \(30 - 50\%\) interest on Neon and surrounding licenses have begun. Subject to FEED progress and a successful farm down, FID is targeted for 2H26. Activities on Who Dat East include resource development planning, facilities design engineering, and cost estimation, with the aim of achieving FID in late 2025/early 2026.
Maintain Overweight rating: Our June 2026 price target is in line with our DCF valuation using a \(10\%\) WACC.

KAR reported a strong 1H25 result, with underlying EBITDA of \(\) 196m\(and NPAT of\) \ \(45m\) , both ahead of expectations. The beat was primarily driven by inventory movements of US \(\) 17.2m\(and flotel and FPSO costs taken below the line. FY25 production guidance was revised upward by\) 4\% \(at the midpoint, despite issues with the electrical submersible pump at SPS - 92, resulting in a\) 10\% \(reduction in FY25 unit production cost guidance.
Figure 1: Historical and forecast underlying EBITDA US\ \(m\)
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Company data.

KAR is concentrating on organic growth opportunities Neon and Who Dat East. The company has initiated discussions with external parties to potentially farm down a \(30 - 50\%\) interest in Neon and its surrounding licenses. If FEED progresses well and the farm down is successful, FID is anticipated for 2H26. For Who Dat East, activities are focused on resource development planning, facilities design engineering, and cost estimation, with the aim of reaching FID in late 2025/early 2026. While we include a risk weighted valuation for Neon, Who Dat East is not included and is potential upside to our numbers.
Figure 3: Production outlook (Mmbce)
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Company data.

With the Bauna FPSO acquisition complete, KAR increased Bauna 2P reserves by \(35\%\) compared to December 2024. This analysis extends Bauna's economic life from 2032 to 2039. KAR plans to invest US \(55 - 65m\) in an FPSO revitalization campaign in 2026 and approximately US \(80 - 90m\) for life extension activities between 2030 and 2034. Abandonment costs have increased from US \(174.9m\) in 2032 to US \(260.0m\) in 2039.
Figure 2: Quarterly Bauna production and reserves (mmboe)
Source: Company reports and J.P. Morgan estimates.

With a clearer outlook at Bauna, the focus shifts towards the transition to operatorship over the next year and advancing growth projects Neon and Who Dat East. While we do see operational risks with KAR taking the reins of the FPSO, we believe KAR is well- positioned to continue improving availability at Bauna, with upside to future production from organic growth. We maintain an Overweight rating.
Figure 4: Composition of our NPV
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have integrated the 1H25 results and the provided guidance, taking into account the implications of acquiring the FPSO and the upgrade of the 2P reserves. As a result, we have lowered our earnings for CY25 and CY26, but have increased our earnings forecasts for 2027. Our NPV has risen by \(9\%\) to \(\) 2.30\(, up from the previous\) \ \(2.10\)
Figure 5: Changes to earnings estimates and valuation
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates
Karoon Energy (Overweight; Price Target: A\(2.30)

We believe Karoon offers good production growth with exploration upside, attractive cash flow generation, a strong balance sheet and an attractive valuation. With the stock price below our NPV, we reiterate our Overweight rating.
Our June 2026 price target is in line with our sum- of- parts DCF valuation using a \(10.4\%\) WACC. We use risk- weighting on unsanctioned projects.
